  "prompt": "Punishment: Why are some prison sentences life plus \"x\" years? (Life + 65 years, for example.)",
  "response": "This practice serves several purposes in the criminal justice system:\n\n1. Consecutive sentencing\n- Ensures that if the defendant is ever released from a life sentence, they will still serve additional time for other crimes\n- Prevents potential early release from negating punishment for multiple offenses\n\n2. Symbolic representation\n- Demonstrates the severity of multiple serious crimes\n- Shows the total culpability of the offender beyond the life sentence\n\n3. Practical legal considerations\n- Prevents potential legal challenges if the life sentence is overturned\n- Provides a clear record of total criminal conduct\n\n4. Potential future scenarios\n- If a life sentence is reduced or overturned, the additional years remain\n- Ensures a minimum guaranteed time served\n\n5. Victim and public perception\n- Communicates the gravity of the crimes committed\n- Provides a sense that justice has been more comprehensively served\n\nIn essence, the additional years act as a legal and symbolic safeguard, ensuring that even if circumstances change regarding the life sentence, the offender will still serve significant additional time for their criminal actions.",
